  "prompt": "Epics of India: Is it true that peacocks don't mate physically?",
  "response": "Yes, it is a common belief in Indian folklore and some ancient texts that peacocks do not mate physically. Instead, it is said that the peahen conceives by drinking the tears of the peacock or by the peacock\u2019s gaze. This myth is often found in Hindu mythology and poetic symbolism, where the peacock is associated with beauty, purity, and mysticism.\n\nHowever, from a biological perspective, peacocks (the males) and peahens (the females) do mate physically, just like other birds. The myth is more of a symbolic or cultural narrative rather than a scientific fact. It reflects the poetic and spiritual imagination of ancient Indian traditions rather than the actual behavior of these birds.",
